Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! We=E2=80=99re back with the third Weekly Dose of Optimism.=20
Not Boring=E2=80=99s mission is to make the world more optimistic.
While the daily headlines can be bleak, and often reflect the genuinely bad=
 and messy things that happen every day, humans keep fighting our way forwa=
rd. This weekly dose of optimism is a little attempt to highlight some of t=
he progress we=E2=80=99re making.=20
Based on feedback last time:
We=E2=80=99re going to keep doing this =E2=80=94 feedback was overwhelmingl=
y positive.
We=E2=80=99ll drop to five bullets =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99re only playing the=
 hits.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Week 3: July 15, 2022
(1) First Images from the James Webb Space Telescope [https://substack.com/=
redirect/4f5f9388-f051-4596-aae8-bb07bb23f8c1?u=3D16283549]=20
That's something that has been true for every image we've gotten with Webb.=
 We can't take blank sky. Everywhere we look, there's galaxies everywhere.
The release of the first images from the James Webb Space Telescope have ri=
ghtfully captured the world=E2=80=99s attention over the past week.=20
The images are so powerful because they=E2=80=99re simultaneously a reminde=
r of how tiny we are in the scheme of the universe and how unique and incre=
dible we are.=20
Tiny. That image on the right of SMACS 0723 is a cluster of whole galaxies =
that represent a fraction of the sky that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Capproximately =
the size of a grain of sand held at arm's length, a tiny sliver of the vast=
 universe.=E2=80=9D The images show light emitted as long as 13 billion yea=
rs ago, less than a billion years after the Big Bang. Each of us, if we=E2=
=80=99re lucky, will live for 0.0000007246% of the history of the universe =
to date, on a planet that inhabits 0.00000000000000000000000000000000000003=
% of the total mass of the universe [https://substack.com/redirect/2de7f1fa=
-88de-4e9d-9d05-0ad6b1248109?u=3D16283549] (and on a small sliver of that p=
lanet, no less).=20
Unique and Incredible. Somehow, despite our numerical insignificance, human=
s have been able to build tools to see into the deepest nooks and crannies =
of the universe, to essentially look backwards in time billions of years, u=
sing just the resources available to us on this little planet. We=E2=80=99r=
e the only intelligent life that we know of in the universe. And we=E2=80=
=99re gearing up to begin our expansion to Mars and beyond. All of that pro=
gress is based on centuries of compounding human experimentation and knowle=
dge, and our knowledge is compounding faster than ever. Humans rock.=20
(2) Space Bubbles Might Be an Emergency Solution to Climate Change [https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/00383c8c-4eb5-4fff-b302-617debae02b9?u=3D16283549]
From: MIT Senseable City Lab=20
Submitted by: Dhruv Sarin [https://substack.com/redirect/10cbcbe5-1933-449c=
-832e-793e16794619?u=3D16283549]
Space-based solutions would be safer =E2=80=93 for instance, if we deflect =
1.8% of incident solar radiation before it hits our planet, we could fully =
reverse today's global warming.
Space research and exploration benefits Earth, too.
A cross-disciplinary team at MIT has developed an =E2=80=9Ceasily deployabl=
e and fully reversible=E2=80=9D tool to deflect solar radiation: Space Bubb=
les. The bubbles could be manufactured directly in outer space, forming an =
extensive deflective raft positioned at the Lagrangian Point=C2=A0between t=
he Earth and the Sun, where the gravity of the two bodies counteract each o=
ther such that small bodies (like space bubbles) will remain approximately =
at rest relative to them. In English, that means that we can make space bub=
bles in space and form them into radiation-blocking shields that would rema=
in where they=E2=80=99re supposed to relative to the earth.=20
While Space Bubbles are an emergency solution, and aren=E2=80=99t a replace=
ment for other climate change mitigation efforts (they wouldn=E2=80=99t giv=
e us that cheap, abundant energy we need anyway), it=E2=80=99s nice to know=
 that we have potential backup plans.=20
(3) Power Moves: Why Private Billions Are Flowing Into Fusion [https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/d4bfd0d3-1039-403a-8ff9-55d183ce5dff?u=3D16283549] (Video=
)
By: Alan Jeffries for Bloomberg
One thing is for sure though: progress, however slow and incremental, is be=
ing made. And if we=E2=80=99re going to get to a fusion-powered future, we=
=E2=80=99re probably going to need the painstaking research and the risky n=
ew ideas.
Nuclear fusion =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe process by which two light atomic nuc=
lei combine to form a single heavier one while releasing massive amounts of=
 energy=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 is the holy grail energy source. Fusion is how t=
he sun makes energy, and harnessing it would be a major step towards cheap,=
 abundant energy.=20
Historically, government-funded research has driven progress in the field. =
Today, fusion startups are getting more funding than ever before, with 20 d=
eals representing $2.98 billion in funding in the space in 2021, including =
Commonwealth Fusion Systems [https://substack.com/redirect/38fe44dc-5632-4f=
65-8e39-ac2ce08a608e?u=3D16283549]=E2=80=99 $1.8 billion Series B in Decemb=
er. The video highlights startups General Fusion [https://substack.com/redi=
rect/d7d28869-641a-47d4-878b-64f8c38925c0?u=3D16283549], Helion [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/53dc1a52-c4e6-4aa6-9821-8268ca0af179?u=3D16283549], and=
 First Light Fusion [https://substack.com/redirect/8ba131d2-ed51-40fd-81b6-=
5e66da4d6f39?u=3D16283549].
Fusion is experiencing the classic government-private sector tug-of-war tha=
t Rahul wrote about in Making Moonshots [https://substack.com/redirect/13cd=
018c-2f27-429a-9b01-b89a93c48f5d?u=3D16283549] =E2=80=94 startups feel that=
 government research will be too slow to get to Net Gain at scale, and gove=
rnment-backed researchers feel that many startups are taking approaches tha=
t won=E2=80=99t work and promising overly aggressive timelines.=20
As the narrator highlights, solving commercial fusion will take both resear=
ch and commercialization. However it happens, it seems that there=E2=80=99s=
 consensus that we=E2=80=99re at most two to three decades away, which is m=
ind-blowing, and could help bring about the benefits of abundant energy tha=
t both Eli Dourado & Austin Vernon [https://substack.com/redirect/b083ceb6-=
d686-4d66-9538-fd972db689cc?u=3D16283549] and Cleo Abram & Matt Yglesias [h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/12ec2b22-4480-4e56-bfee-6cf8145ef784?u=3D16283=
549] describe well. =20
(4) Guinea worm disease is close to being eradicated =E2=80=93 how was this=
 progress achieved? [https://substack.com/redirect/9342f752-7baa-418d-b437-=
dfc41dd51303?u=3D16283549]
By: Saloni Dattani and Fiona Spooner for Our World in Data
Submitted by: Titian Steiger [https://substack.com/redirect/4ab073d8-ce34-4=
81e-b4e7-f92c3108c5a4?u=3D16283549]
Despite these challenges, there has been a massive decline in guinea worm c=
ases over time. Only 15 cases were reported globally in 2021. After thousan=
ds of years, the entire world may soon be free of this debilitating disease=
=2E
=E2=80=9CGuinea worm disease is a painful and debilitating disease that use=
d to be common in Asia, the Middle East, and many countries in Africa.=C2=
=A0
It=E2=80=99s now close to being eradicated worldwide. This success is thank=
s to an eradication program that has focused on water treatment and filtrat=
ion, public education, and providing safe sources of drinking water to redu=
ce its spread.=E2=80=9D=20
The first three pieces in this newsletter are about making progress by push=
ing the frontiers of science. This one is about applying things that we=E2=
=80=99ve known for a long time. In the 1980s, there were nearly a million c=
ases of Guinea worm disease per year. That=E2=80=99s a big number, but what=
 it means is that each year, a million humans swallowed parasitic eggs that=
 =E2=80=9Cmature into adult worms =E2=80=93 with female worms growing up to=
 around a meter in length =E2=80=93 and crawl through people=E2=80=99s conn=
ective tissue, joints, and bones.=E2=80=9D One in 200 of them were left wit=
h a permanent debilitating disease. And now, through education and clean wa=
ter, the disease is all but gone, with only 15 reported cases last year.=20
(5) 6 Breakthroughs Defeating Cancer [https://substack.com/redirect/6c80abb=
d-0bbe-4f2f-bff2-ac4ff775ee0f?u=3D16283549]
By: Peter Diamandis [https://substack.com/redirect/91350510-bdcd-4247-b55c-=
e372186d0da2?u=3D16283549]
Submitted by: Brad Power [https://substack.com/redirect/bee57a88-c45b-4117-=
855a-c0c58e45032c?u=3D16283549]
The convergence of synthetic biology, genomics, AI/machine learning, cellul=
ar medicines, and immunotherapy have ushered in a new era of truly personal=
ized medicine.=C2=A0We are edging closer to a dramatically different reacti=
on to the =E2=80=9CBig C=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94cancer. Pretty soon, this equal-o=
pportunity scourge will be a thing of the past.
Fuck cancer. This year, approximately 9.5 million people around the world w=
ill die from cancer. In the US alone, there will be about 1.9 million new c=
ases this year, and about one-third of those people will die from cancer th=
is year. And it=E2=80=99s personal: almost everyone reading this knows some=
one close to them afflicted by cancer.=20
But this piece suggests that =E2=80=9Cthere are reasons to believe we can c=
ure it within the next 10 years=E2=80=9D and lays out 6 promising treatment=
s to track:=20
Checkpoint Inhibitors
Personalized Cancer Vaccines=20
Natural Killer Cells Harvested From Human Placentas
ECDNA Targeted Therapy=20
Synthetic Lethality=20
Food & Our Microbiome
Many of these treatments are promising but still early =E2=80=94 tested in =
mice or small groups of humans =E2=80=94 but they=E2=80=99re worth followin=
g.=20
Personally, I=E2=80=99m excited to see the prevention and treatments, for c=
ancer and beyond, made possible by the dramatically declining cost of genet=
ic sequencing. Yesterday, Not Boring Capital portfolio company Nucleus anno=
unced its $14 million Seed+ [https://substack.com/redirect/1e834878-1cc9-46=
ee-8ae2-3c213e3fceda?u=3D16283549] from 776, Founders Fund, Shrug, and more=
 to put =E2=80=9Ca human genome on every smartphone.=E2=80=9D=20
Bonus: For All Mankind on Apple TV+ [https://substack.com/redirect/3ba23ce2=
-c5d2-4bc6-bb72-2daaea069d15?u=3D16283549]
Given all of the focus on space this week, this feels like the right time t=
o recommend my latest streaming obsession: For All Mankind. The show =E2=80=
=9Cimagines a world where the space race never ended.=E2=80=9D As we=E2=80=
=99ve written about before [https://substack.com/redirect/53aec9f3-6f6b-43b=
8-8773-c5129bf5f446?u=3D16283549], this year marks the 50 year anniversary =
of the last time a human set foot on the moon. For All Mankind presents an =
alternate history, one in which NASA, Russia, and private companies continu=
e to travel to the moon, and beyond.=20
The show fits this newsletter=E2=80=99s optimism theme so well because whil=
e it celebrates human progress, it also presents all of the challenges and =
fights and struggles that arise in space and at home in the pursuit. Progre=
ss is bumpy, but it=E2=80=99s important.=20
Double Bonus: Arkive=E2=80=99s Tom McCleod on Not Boring Founders [https://=
substack.com/redirect/b37d9801-6a2b-41d3-85da-d7d06ab2ed88?u=3D16283549]
We talk about a lot of science, but I=E2=80=99m excited about the world get=
ting more fun, collaborative, and culturally rich, too. This week, Not Bori=
ng Capital portfolio company Arkive [https://substack.com/redirect/1ba47fed=
-1510-4ed2-bd70-49c94a6b15a1?u=3D16283549] announced its $9.7 million Seed =
=E2=80=9Cto build the world=E2=80=99s first decentralized physical museum c=
urated & operated by its members.=E2=80=9D Its first purchase is the patent=
 for the ENIAC computer. As humans produce more amazing culture and knowled=
ge, Arkive will buy them and make sure they=E2=80=99re on public display fo=
r more people to learn from. Listen to the episode with Tom [https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/5c4a295b-b9ab-4c25-a6ea-9f09909a217e?u=3D16283549] to learn=
 more and get involved [https://substack.com/redirect/34d7a3b4-d849-43e1-a9=
81-142334f749fd?u=3D16283549].
Good work out there this week, fellow humans.=20
We can=E2=80=99t find all of the best things humanity accomplished every we=
ek on our own =E2=80=94 help us out by submitting the things you come acros=
s that make you most optimistic here [https://substack.com/redirect/68f82b0=
f-6e0d-449c-b506-2a7c209c67cf?u=3D16283549].
Have a great weekend!=20
